            {"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The water cycle, also known as the hydrological cycle, describes the continuous movement of water through Earth's systems. It is driven primarily by solar energy and gravity, and it plays a fundamental role in sustaining life on our planet."}]},
            {"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The cycle begins with "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"evaporation"},{"type":"text","text":" — the process by which liquid water from oceans, lakes, and rivers is converted into water vapor by the sun's heat. This vapor rises into the atmosphere, where it cools and undergoes "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"condensation"},{"type":"text","text":", forming clouds and fog."}]},
            {"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"When water droplets in clouds combine and grow heavy enough, they fall back to Earth as "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"precipitation"},{"type":"text","text":" — rain, snow, sleet, or hail, depending on atmospheric temperature. Some of this water flows over the land surface as "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"runoff"},{"type":"text","text":", eventually reaching rivers and oceans. Some seeps into the ground, replenishing "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"groundwater"},{"type":"text","text":" reserves."}]},
            {"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Plants also play a role through "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"transpiration"},{"type":"text","text":" — releasing water vapor through their leaves. Together, evaporation and transpiration are referred to as "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"evapotranspiration"},{"type":"text","text":". The cycle then repeats, ensuring a continuous redistribution of fresh water across the planet."}]}
          ]
